  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's something I've seen play out in the real world, especially with my own students and clients. Growing up in a family where my father had no formal education but my mother worked hard in the service industry, I learned early that people often judge you based on what they think you're capable of. When I first started working in hairdressing, I noticed how some people would assume I wasn't good at technical tasks because of my background. That same kind of bias can creep into STEM fields, where people from underrepresented groups feel the pressure of negative stereotypes about their abilities. For example, a girl in my community might avoid math because she's worried she'll be seen as 'not smart enough'—a classic case of stereotype threat. I believe we absolutely must address this issue. It's not just about fixing a problem; it's about creating a more inclusive environment where everyone feels valued. In my small town, we've started workshops where kids from diverse backgrounds can explore STEM without the fear of judgment. These sessions focus on building confidence through hands-on activities, like building simple robots or coding games, which helps them see themselves as capable. The key is to make sure that the message isn't 'you can't do this' but 'you belong here.' My anxiety sometimes makes me worry about whether my efforts will make a difference, but I know that even small changes can have a big impact. If we can help young people feel safe and supported in STEM, we're not just changing their lives—we're changing the future of innovation.",
